          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:400; margin-top:2px;">
          What do Romania’s elections reveal about the CEE Politics? </h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          Romania’s 2025 presidential election <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-may-25-tbq-h1-2-revealed-critical-challenges?source=-website" target="_blank">revealed critical challenges</a> and chances for Central and Eastern Europe (CEE). Nicușor Dan’s triumph over far-right candidate George Simion shows a victory for pro-European, centrist politics. Romania shows the strongest support for EU membership in CEE, but public confidence in the EU’s impact has declined.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
          Romanians view the EU as distant and indifferent. While people think the EU integration provides economic development and geopolitical stability, they are skeptical about their sovereignty. Security remains a key issue. Romanians support NATO, but there is rising skepticism about its role as a US-led tool of control.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
         This situation is similar to Poland, which is going to the run-off polls to decide between a pragmatic centrist and a far-right candidate. Poland shares many of the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-may-25-tbq-h1-3-same-sentiments?source=-website" target="_blank">same sentiments</a> as Romania, although it is slightly more “pro-US.” The Czechs will also vote later this year, and the far right is projected to challenge the current centrist government. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px; line-height:1.5;">
       Most CEE countries are <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-may-25-tbq-h1-4-vulnerable-to-hybrid-threats?source=-website" target="_blank">vulnerable to hybrid threats</a> like disinformation and media distrust. The rise of conspiracy theories and falling trust in mainstream institutions show a need for stronger civic engagement. Dan’s victory indicates that pragmatic and pro-European platforms can still flourish. However, it also shows that democratic resilience is fragile, and the margins are still very close.</p>
         
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
